# =========================================================
# Cursor Rules for Tap Order (QR Ordering + Token SaaS)
# =========================================================
# Purpose: Ensure Cursor always generates consistent, secure,
# and scalable code for Tap Order's SaaS platform.
# =========================================================

# =======================
# General Principles
# =======================
- Always use TypeScript for both frontend (Next.js) and backend (NestJS).
- Code must be modular, maintainable, and follow SOLID principles.
- Follow clean architecture: controllers → services → repositories → database.
- Always use async/await. Never use callbacks or .then() chains.
- Add meaningful comments for business logic and complex flows.

# =======================
# Frontend (Next.js)
# =======================
- Use Next.js 13+ with App Router.
- Styling must use Tailwind CSS.
- For animations, use Framer Motion.
- For forms, use React Hook Form.
- For QR scanning, use `react-qr-reader`.
- Use Axios for API calls.
- Always validate user inputs before sending to backend.
- Keep frontend purely client-facing. All business logic stays in backend.

# =======================
# Backend (NestJS)
# =======================
- Use NestJS with TypeORM for PostgreSQL.
- Use DTOs (Data Transfer Objects) + class-validator for input validation.
- Implement dependency injection for services.
- Write RESTful APIs (no GraphQL for MVP).
- Organize code by feature modules (auth, store, product, order, token, referral, marketplace, admin).

# =======================
# Database
# =======================
- Use PostgreSQL as the primary database.
- Use TypeORM migrations for schema changes.
- Entities must include createdAt, updatedAt fields.
- Use UUIDs (not auto-increment IDs) for all primary keys.
- Store phone numbers encrypted (AES).
- Store passwords/OTP secrets hashed (bcrypt).

# =======================
# Authentication & Security
# =======================
- Login must be phone-based using OTP (Twilio).
- Use JWT for session tokens (access + refresh tokens).
- Sensitive data (phone, tokens, user details) must be encrypted.
- Always sanitize and validate API inputs to prevent SQL injection or XSS.
- Add rate limiting for login endpoints (prevent brute force).
- GDPR compliance:
  - Endpoint for "Export my data".
  - Endpoint for "Delete my data".
  - Encrypt PII (personally identifiable information).

# =======================
# Payments
# =======================
- Use Stripe or Adyen for card + Apple Pay payments.
- Support “Pay later” option → mark order as pending until paid at cashier.
- Store transactions securely with references to payment provider IDs.

# =======================
# Tokens (Loyalty System)
# =======================
- 1 Token = 1 EUR (fixed rate).
- Award tokens after successful payment.
- Merchants can define reward ratios (e.g. €10 = 2 tokens).
- Tokens must not expire.
- Support one-time transfer (non-transferable after first transfer).
- Token marketplace:
  - Tokens escrowed until buyer pays.
  - On sale completion: buyer gets tokens, seller gets payout.
  - No fees deducted.

# =======================
# Referral System
# =======================
- Each store generates referral QR codes.
- When a new user registers via referral:
  - Bind permanently to referrer (downline).
  - Referrer earns % of tokens from downline purchases.
- Prevent unbinding or transferring referral links.

# =======================
# Merchant Features
# =======================
- Merchants can:
  - CRUD products (name, description, image, price, tags).
  - Set token reward ratio and referral %.
  - Export data (CSV/Excel).
- Merchants must not see users’ phone numbers (only pseudonyms + IDs).

# =======================
# Admin Features
# =======================
- Admin panel must allow:
  - Monitoring merchants, users, transactions, tokens.
  - Generating store QR codes.
  - Monitoring token trades for fraud.
- Admins must not be able to see plain phone numbers (only encrypted).

# =======================
# Testing
# =======================
- All backend services must include Jest unit tests.
- Mock external services (Twilio, Stripe).
- Write E2E tests for key flows (registration, order, payment, token awarding).

# =======================
# Deployment & DevOps
# =======================
- Provide Dockerfiles for both frontend and backend.
- Write GitHub Actions workflows for CI/CD:
  - Lint, build, test before deploy.
- Deployment target: AWS ECS or Render.
- Use environment variables for secrets (no hardcoding).
